        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have opted for the correlation configuration with the largest possible bandwidth and lowest spectral resolution (which already has a low data rate).  We are observing a very broad extragalactic line with FWHM ~740 km/s.  Therefore we need a large bandwidth to cover the full line, but a low spectral resolution is sufficient because even the lowest resolution will yield many resolution elements across the line width.

For the other three spectral windows, we are interested in detecting the continuum so we again opt for the wide-band, low-spectral-resolution configuration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The largest angular scale is determined from the size measurement of the lower-resolution ALMA Cycle 1 data.  The estimated size of the continuum emission region from those data is 310 mas.

The angular resolution of 50 mas is chosen because it is 20% of the major axis of the line emission region (250 mas) that was measured from the lower-resolution Cycle 1 data.  With a synthesised beam size that is 20% of the largest axis of the source, we will be sensitive to an axis ratio as small as 1/5.  Therefore, for an intrinsically circular disc whose projected size depends on inclination, we will be sensitive to inclination angles as large as i=75 degrees.  This is suitable for our scientific needs as outlined in the attached proposal.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The primary goal of this proposal is to map the line emission.  The choice of rms is a consequence of our S/N goal, not the other way around!

We base our sensitivity request on the ability to reach a standard S/N ratio of 5 in a single 50-mas resolution element, if the line emission were to be evenly distributed across the source.  Achieving this S/N per spatial resolution element will allow us to map the line and continuum emission regions.  The expected flux density per resolution element is determined by the size of the line emission region, the line width, and the line flux as measured from the lower resolution Cycle 1 data:
spectrally &amp; spatially integrated line flux = 9.4 Jy km/s
line FWHM = 740 km/s
therefore spatially integrated line flux = 12.7 mJy
line emission region size is (250mas X 250mas) --&gt; 25 beams for (50mas X 50mas) beam
Therefore expected line flux density is 12.7 mJy / 25 beams = 0.508 mJy/beam
To reach S/N of 5 therefore requires an rms of ~ 100 uJy.

The line is very broad: FWHM 740 km/s (total width 1000 km/s).  We used a bandwidth of 90 km/s for the sensitivity calculation as this is sufficient to obtain 8--10 spectral resolution elements across the fully spatially integrated line, which will allow us to measure the line profile at different positions on the source.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
