    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe QSO J1554+1937 with high spatial resolution to map its
[CII] line and continuum. This QSO at z=4.627 is one of the most luminous known
(Lbol &gt; 10^14 Lsun), with an extremely massive central black hole. By studying
such extreme QSOs, we probe the limits of an important source
population. Lower-spatial-resolution observations obtained in an earlier
ALMA cycle (PI Kimball) already revealed remarkable results. The velocity map
and profile of the [CII] line suggest that it originates from a rotating disc,
with no sign of extended emission from outflowing gas, though outflows are
thought to be ubiquitous in luminous QSOs. The line is broad (FWHM ~740 kms),
indicating a high maximum circular velocity of ~480 km/s. These results have
important implications for the host galaxy's properties, but are subject to the
disc origin hypothesis and unknown disc inclination. With the proposed
high-resolution observations, we will: look for signatures of outflowing gas on
scales that were unresolved in the earlier data; test the validity of the disc
hypothesis; and then (if confirmed) determine its inclination, allowing us to
better constrain the host galaxy properties.</prp:abstract>
